1
00:00:03,000 --> 00:00:07,000
下一位講者是遠道從東京而來

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:11,000
也是 try! Swift Tokyo 的主辦人 Daiki Matsudate

3
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:15,000
他擁有 14 年以上的 App 開發經驗

4
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:21,000
目前從事從新創到公共數位服務的各種專案

5
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:25,000
今天演講一樣是用英文來進行

6
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:29,000
讓我們用最最熱烈的掌聲歡迎我們國外的朋友 Daiki

7
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:50,000
 Hi, I'm Daiki from Tokyo, Japan, where I organize try! Swift, an international Swift conference

8
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:56,000
 It's my first time back in Taipei since speaking at iPlayground in 2019

9
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:00,000
 I'm happy to reconnect with many friends from Taiwan

10
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:04,000
 Thank you to the organizers for such a great event

11
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:10,000
 Today, I'll talk about identity verification on mobile devices

12
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:16,000
 We prove who are using identity documents issued by public authorities

13
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:18,000
 For example, this is my passport

14
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:24,000
 It's an official document issued by the Japanese government that certifies who I am

15
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:34,000
 With this, even here in Taipei, I can prove that I am Daiki Matsudate, born in January 31, 1991, and citizen of Japan

16
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:40,000
 And this is Japan's My Number card, another official identity document issued by the government

17
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:47,000
 On the surface, it shows my name, address, date of birth, gender, and identification number

18
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:57,000
 But more importantly, it contains a tamper-resistant IC chip that securely stores this information, along with two digital certificates

19
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:07,000
 These certificates make it possible not only to visually check the card, but also to electronically verify my identity and even create digital signatures

20
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:18,000
 All of these are called identity documents, and identity documents are used to uniquely identify a person

21
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:32,000
 It must be issued by an authorized organization, and it typically includes portrait and personal information, either printed on the card or stored in an electronic method

22
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:41,000
 Now, this is a scene from a Netflix drama called Tokyo Swindlers, which became a hot topic in Japan

23
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:51,000
 In this story, a certificate issued by a local government and a driver's license issued by the police office are used for identity verification

24
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:56,000
 But in fact, there were fake documents created by swindlers

25
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:04,000
 They even hired a homeless person to use a fake name and portrait as a property owner in order to say the land actually did not exist

26
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:10,000
 This drama is fictional, but based on true events

27
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:16,000
 In reality, document forgery like this has been a serious problem in Japan

28
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:26,000
 To prevent such crimes, we need stronger measures, such as using IC chips to electronically verify identity, not just checking the card surface

29
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:44,000
 Against this backdrop, many countries began exploring ways to store a driver's license on mobile devices, and in 2021, this effort was standardized internationally as ISO 18013-5

30
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:52,000
 When the mDL standard was created, several key features were introduced

31
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:55,000
 First is selective data disclosure of elements

32
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:15,000
 For example, if all you need to know is whether someone is over 18 to buy alcohol in-store, there is no need to reveal their date of birth

33
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:21,000
 Instead, the mDL can list only the elements that say age over 18

34
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:25,000
 Next is cryptographic security

35
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:31,000
 The mDL is structured in a format called C-B-O-R, which pronounces CBOR

36
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:40,000
 The signatures are encoded using C-O-S-E, which pronounces COSE, which stands for CBOR Object Signing and Encryption

37
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:46,000
 Some of you may be hearing about CBOR for the first time

38
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:48,000
 CBOR is a type of date format

39
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:54,000
 It has a structure similar to JSON, but while JSON is expressed, CBOR is a binary format

40
00:04:54,000 --> 00:05:03,000
 Because of this, data encoded in CBOR is typically 30 to 50 percent smaller compared to JSON

41
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:15,000
 This compact size makes CBOR especially suitable for IoT devices and mobile platforms, where efficiency matters and battery life can be improved

42
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:20,000
 There is also cross-platform interoperability

43
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:28,000
 mDLs can be used over NFC, BLE, QR codes, and the internet, so they work seamlessly across different platforms

44
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:33,000
 Privacy is also a key focus

45
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:42,000
 No data can be accessed without the user consent, which is enforced through biometric authentications like Face ID or Touch ID

46
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:54,000
 Based on this standard, Apple and Google have begun working with the U.S. states to store driver's licenses as mDLs in their wallet apps

47
00:05:54,000 --> 00:06:04,000
 Since driver's licenses in the United States are issued by each individual state, support differs depending on the state

48
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:11,000
 In some states, they can use Apple wallets, in others, Google wallets, and in some cases, both

49
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:19,000
 The standard for mDL was later expanded for more use with other identity documents

50
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:25,000
 In 2023, this became standard as a mobile identity document, mDOC for short

51
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:36,000
 For such as passports, insurance cards, and student IDs beyond driver's licenses, the feature is the same as mDL

52
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:46,000
 Using these two standards, Our Japan enabled the My Number Card to be used on iPhones, starting in June this year

53
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:53,000
 This was made possible through collaboration between the Digital Agency, the government of Japan, and Apple

54
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:00,000
 It's the first case in the world where a national ID has been stored on an Apple wallet as mDOC

55
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 This card integrates both mDOC functionality and electronic certificates into a single device-bound wallet item

56
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:17,000
 This digital credential adheres to global world ID standards, as I mentioned

57
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:23,000
 Apps can access mDOC using APIs from Apple

58
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:30,000
 These allow apps to request identity or age data within wallets, prompting user consent

59
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:38,000
 I won't go into the details of certificates today, since it's specific to our local use cases

60
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:44,000
 Instead, I'd like to show you how we can use Apple's API to retrieve an mDOC

61
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:49,000
 The Apple provides three main APIs

62
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:52,000
 Each is provided by the...

63
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:54,000
 Sorry

64
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:59,000
 Also, different contexts in app, in person, and in the web browser

65
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:03,000
 So today, I want to be covering the third one

66
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:07,000
 This was introduced at this year's WWDC session

67
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:12,000
 It allows you to request an mDOC directly from the browser, even without an iPhone

68
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:16,000
 Check it out if you are interested

69
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:20,000
 So let's start with Verify with Wallet

70
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:27,000
 Verify with Wallet is a method for requesting an mDOC from wallets within your app

71
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:33,000
 The retrieved data can then be used directly inside the app

72
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:39,000
 Because of this, using this API requires a special entitlement for app

73
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:44,000
 The data is encrypted in HPKE format

74
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:50,000
 And neither Apple nor Wallet can decrypt the information inside

75
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:54,000
 Verify with... Oh, sorry

76
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:56,000
 Yes

77
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:00,000
 There are two entitlements required to call this API

78
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:04,000
 The first one is In-App Identity Presentment

79
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:11,000
 With this entitlement, you must specify which documents you want to access

80
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:15,000
 For example, US driver's license or Japan's national ID

81
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:23,000
 You also need to specify which elements you plan to read, such as name, portrait, or age

82
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:30,000
 If what you request at runtime doesn't match what you applied for in advance

83
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:33,000
 the API call will be rejected

84
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:42,000
 The other entitlement requires you to specify a merchant ID

85
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:50,000
 This merchant ID is different from the app ID, you use for Apple Pay or Apple Wallet

86
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:57,000
 When you generate it from the Apple developer portal, you link it to bundle ID of the app

87
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:05,000
 To use Verify with Wallet, your app must call the API and request the user's approval

88
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:11,000
 Once approved, Wallet returns an object encrypted with HPKE

89
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:17,000
 You then send this object to your own server where it's decrypted

90
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:22,000
 After decryption, the payload is in C format

91
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:27,000
 From it, you can obtain the elements you requested

92
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:32,000
 The API provided by Apple is included in PassKit

93
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:38,000
 In the descriptor, you specify the element you need

94
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:46,000
 In the request object, you set the descriptor and the region

95
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:49,000
 At this point, you also configure the merchant ID

96
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:53,000
 When you send the data request to the controller

97
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:57,000
 the user screen  a seed asking for permission to share the information

98
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:01,000
 They will approve it with Face ID or Touch ID

99
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:10,000
 Once the user approves, you receive an HPKE envelope, as defined in RFC 9180

100
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:16,000
 This envelope combines public key encryption with symmetric encryption

101
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:19,000
 providing a secure way to encrypt and decrypt the data

102
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:25,000
 You then send this envelope to your server for decryption

103
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:32,000
 When you decrypt this data, the resulting structure is C-Board

104
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:38,000
 As you look into the data, you'll find that the given name field contains a value

105
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:44,000
 This is the kind of data your app can then use directly

106
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:46,000
 And that's Verify with Wallet

107
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:52,000
 It's an API you can use for in-app identity verification

108
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:55,000
 For more details, please check out the WWDC 22 session

109
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:58,000
 What's New in Wallet and Apple Pay

110
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:10,000
 I didn't go into details today about how to request entitlements or how to test with a simulator or on devices

111
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:15,000
 But you can find all of this explained in more details on Apple developers' website

112
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:22,000
 So next, let's talk about ID Verifier API

113
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:25,000
 This API uses two iPhones

114
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:26,000
 The reader iPhone sends an ID to the reader

115
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:30,000
 The reader iPhone sends an mDOC request to the holder

116
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:34,000
 and the user presents their iPhone in response

117
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:39,000
 When the iPhone is tapped to the reader

118
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:42,000
 NFC is used to initiate a BLE connection

119
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:49,000
 Through this BLE connection, the mDOC is transmitted

120
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:52,000
 The API provides two modes

121
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:56,000
 display request and data transfer

122
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:59,000
 With the display request

123
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:03,000
 you can retrieve elements like portrait, age, and name

124
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:08,000
 For age, you can specify whether you want the actual age

125
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:11,000
 or just checking over a certain age

126
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:16,000
 The requested information is shown on the screen only

127
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:20,000
 Your app itself does not retrieve the data

128
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:25,000
 No special entitlement request is required

129
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:30,000
 As long as you enable the ID Verifier display capability in your app

130
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:33,000
 you can use this feature right away

131
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:36,000
 On the other hand, with data transfer

132
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:41,000
 you can obtain additional elements such as date of birth

133
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:45,000
 address, and sex on the top, the ones I mentioned earlier

134
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:51,000
 Their elements are then transferred directly into your app

135
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:56,000
 Unlike the display request

136
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:59,000
 this mode lets your app actually access the data

137
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:06,000
 That means you need to request a special entitlement from Apple called Proximity Reader Identity Lead

138
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:15,000
 The ID Verifier API is provided through a framework called Proximity Reader

139
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:21,000
 Compared to PassKit, it looks and feels like a much more modern API

140
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:26,000
 Just like with Verify with Wallet

141
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:28,000
 we specify the elements we want to retrieve

142
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:32,000
 When we call prepare on the reader

143
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:33,000
 we get the session needs for the request

144
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:37,000
 Then we call the request on this session

145
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:44,000
 The user is asked to present their ID by holding the iPhone for the reader

146
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:48,000
 Next is a data request

147
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:50,000
 It has almost the same as the previous one

148
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:57,000
 but the difference is whether the requested information can be retained for a certain period of time

149
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:01,000
 A small detail, but starting from iOS 26

150
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:05,000
 we can use a protocol so that calls can be more shortened

151
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:11,000
 With a data request, the response is strongly typed

152
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:14,000
 so you can retrieve the data easily

153
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:22,000
 In most cases, using the reader requires issuing a token

154
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:24,000
 to authenticate the reader itself

155
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:31,000
 This token is passed into the prepare method to be verified

156
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:35,000
 This is also a raw data request

157
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:38,000
 In addition to the standard data request

158
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:41,000
 it handles raw mDOC data

159
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:46,000
 but there is no time to introduce you to it at this time

160
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:53,000
 I have shown you how to perform in-person identity verification sing the ID Verifier API

161
00:15:55,000 --> 00:15:57,000
 For more details, please check out the WWDC23 session

162
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:00,000
 What's New in Wallet and Apple Pay

163
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:04,000
 Just like with Verify with Wallet

164
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:07,000
 details such as how to request entitlements

165
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:11,000
 or how to test are available from the Apple Developer website

166
00:16:13,000 --> 00:16:14,000
 Now in Japan

167
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:20,000
 the digital agency has released an in-person verification app

168
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:25,000
 This app uses the ID Verifier API

169
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:28,000
 Let's take a look at how it works in practice

170
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:34,000
 Can I use the stand

171
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:37,000
 Or somebody may help

172
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:56,000
 Thank you

173
00:16:56,000 --> 00:17:00,000
 There are two iPhones in my hand

174
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:03,000
 This is a holder

175
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:06,000
 which has my number card inside Wallet

176
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:09,000
 This is a reader

177
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:11,000
 which shows installed apps to verify

178
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:17,000
 In the app, select the use case what we want to get from the holder

179
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:21,000
 Then tap Start

180
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:25,000
 The reader shows the UI to be tapped to the iPhone

181
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:29,000
 The holder taps the iPhone on the top

182
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:46,000
 My phone requires passcode, sorry

183
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:05,000
 Okay, this is my ID

184
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:10,000
 The reader requests a tapped iPhone here

185
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:18,000
 The holder has requested authentication with FaceID

186
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:22,000
 The reader shows the UI

187
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:27,000
 And it says I'm over 20

188
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:32,000
 That's it

189
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:37,000
 Let me recap this session

190
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:42,000
 By using the ID card inside the iPhone

191
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:45,000
 we can protect ourselves from more security and safety

192
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:50,000
 Apple provides three kinds of APIs for the situation

193
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:53,000
 In-app, in-person, and web browser

194
00:18:54,000 --> 00:19:01,000
 ID Verifier for in-person provides three kinds of APIs, display data request and load data request

195
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:06,000
 And these APIs are compatible with ISO standards

196
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:14,000
 So we can use three APIs even if published by US driver's license or Japan's my number card

197
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:17,000
 or some new ID card in other countries in future

198
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:20,000
 So that's all

199
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:23,000
 So it was happy to hear and see you again

200
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:26,000
 And hope to see you in Tokyo next time

201
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:27,000
 Thank you so much

